article.description:
Chasity Melvin was an offensive force under the
basket for the Cleveland Rockers.
article.headline: Melvin, Taylor lead Rockers to victory
article.linkText: Melvin helps Rockers keep Shock winless
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Chasity Melvin was an offensive force under the
basket for the Cleveland Rockers.

	   Melvin scored 19 points, including eight on a variety of inside
moves during the Rockers' 29-4 run, as Cleveland beat the winless
Detroit Shock 72-55 on Thursday night.

	   "It was fun to see Chasity impact inside,'' Rockers coach Dan
Hughes said. "She did a nice job of attacking the basket.''

	   Penny Taylor added 16 points and nine rebounds for the Rockers
(1-1), who turned a 17-16 deficit into a 45-21 lead in an 11:14
span.

	   "We did not handle their zone defense very well,'' Shock coach
Greg Williams said. "They were extremely opportunistic on
turnovers, really physical on the inside, and went on that
unbelievable run. It was pretty ugly.''

	   Taylor had five points during a 15-0 run to open the second half
as Detroit went scoreless the first 6:15 of the half until Swin
Cash hit two free throws.

	   Wendy Palmer scored 15 points to lead Detroit (0-5), which
missed its first 11 shots from the field in the second half until
Lenae Williams sank a 3-pointer with 10:57 to play to make it
52-28.

	   "We did a good job of setting the tempo,'' Hughes said. "What
impressed me most was our rebounding.''

	   The Rockers held a 36-23 edge on the boards.

	   "The Cleveland jerseys were jumping and ours were just standing
there watching,'' Williams said.

	   Cash scored 12, but the second pick in April's WNBA draft shot
just 3-for-14 from the field.

	   "When the ball is not going in, you have to penetrate and we
did not do that tonight,'' Cash said.

	   Nevertheless, Taylor was impressed with the rookie from
Connecticut.

	   "She seems like a great player,'' Taylor said. "She's very
athletic, but we prepared for her and were ready.''

	   Cleveland closed the first half with a 14-4 run to lead 30-21.

	   A 10-foot jumper by Merlakia Jones with 4:59 to go in the half
put the Rockers ahead to stay at 18-17. Jones finished with 14
points as the Rockers rebounded from a 69-65 overtime loss to
Houston on Saturday.

	   "You win games when you respond to adversity by practicing hard
and then implementing it,'' Hughes said. "I see this team making
progress.''

	   Cleveland is without four key players from the team that went
22-10 last season and won the Eastern Conference. Center Ann
Wauters has yet to return from playing in Europe, forward Rushia
Brown is out with a broken finger on her right hand and point guard
Helen Darling gave birth to triplets April 13. Forward Eva Nemcova,
the Rockers' career scoring leader, did not re-sign for her sixth
WNBA season.
